  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is depreciation clawback when selling an investment property in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Depreciation clawback refers to the tax obligation that arises when you sell an investment property and the proceeds attributable to depreciable plant and equipment items exceed the remaining written-down tax value of those items. The difference is treated as assessable ordinary income in the year of sale, not as a capital gain. This means it is taxed at your full marginal rate without the benefit of the 50% CGT discount. The longer you have held the property and the more depreciation you have claimed on fixtures and appliances, the more exposure you are likely to have."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does depreciation clawback apply to the building structure or just the fixtures and fittings?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For residential rental properties in Australia, Division 43 capital works deductions claimed on the building structure do not reduce your CGT cost base, so there is no clawback on building deductions when you sell. The clawback mechanism applies to Division 40 plant and equipment items only: appliances, carpets, hot water systems, air conditioning units, blinds, ceiling fans, and other fixtures with individual depreciable values. These are subject to a balancing adjustment at sale that creates assessable ordinary income taxable at your marginal rate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I work out how much depreciation clawback I will face when selling my Brisbane investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Your depreciation schedule, prepared by a quantity surveyor, records the written-down tax value of each plant and equipment item. Before you list, ask your accountant to estimate the likely balancing adjustment by comparing those written-down values against a market value estimate for the fittings at sale. Your accountant should then model the total tax position for the year of sale: the balancing adjustment income at your marginal rate, plus the capital gain after the 50% CGT discount (if eligible), minus any available offsets or deductions. This exercise regularly surfaces five-figure tax obligations that investors had not factored into their net proceeds expectations."
      }
    }
  ]
};
